<span id="freeTextContainer17805624911517333023"><b>4 .5</b><br/><br/>I was drawn to this book because of Barnes&apos; writing and because of the topic. If it sounds odd to say one enjoyed a book about the fear of death/complete-annihilation, so be it. Barnes is entertaining; erudite; and even chuckle-out-loud funny in this book. He writes of his childhood memories, how they differ from those of his brother; how narrative/story both shapes and changes what we remember or what we think we remember; and contemplates the idea of memory = identity.</span>
  <span id="freeText17805624911517333023" style="display:none"><b>4 .5</b><br /><br />I was drawn to this book because of Barnes' writing and because of the topic. If it sounds odd to say one enjoyed a book about the fear of death/complete-annihilation, so be it. Barnes is entertaining; erudite; and even chuckle-out-loud funny in this book. He writes of his childhood memories, how they differ from those of his brother; how narrative/story both shapes and changes what we remember or what we think we remember; and contemplates the idea of memory = identity.</span>
