    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1071080358" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1071080358" />
    <a title="Elizabeth (Alaska)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2026178-elizabeth-alaska"><img alt="Elizabeth (Alaska)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1304966095p2/2026178.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1071080358?book_show_action=true">Dec 15, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth (Alaska)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth (Alaska)" href="/user/show/2026178-elizabeth-alaska">Elizabeth (Alaska)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307389985" href="/book/show/6327610-nothing-to-be-frightened-of">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=twenty-first-century">twenty-first-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2026178-elizabeth-alaska?shelf=5-star-reads">5-star-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1071080358" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3750832819015459539">I like the way Julian Barnes writes, and I want to read more of his fiction. Instead, this is the book that was next for me. Not only did I easily find a place for it in this season&apos;s challenge, but I have reached a point in life where it is worthwhile reading a book about death and dying. No, I haven&apos;t been diagnosed with any long term illness - not even any short term ones. Though I&apos;m past 70, I expect to enjoy some family history of longevity. Still, it&apos;s high time I should have some thoughts</span>
  <span id="freeText3750832819015459539" style="display:none">I like the way Julian Barnes writes, and I want to read more of his fiction. Instead, this is the book that was next for me. Not only did I easily find a place for it in this season's challenge, but I have reached a point in life where it is worthwhile reading a book about death and dying. No, I haven't been diagnosed with any long term illness - not even any short term ones. Though I'm past 70, I expect to enjoy some family history of longevity. Still, it's high time I should have some thoughts on this subject.<br /><br />There are a couple of things I did not expect. I did not expect portions of this to be out loud funny. Most of these include family anecdotes. Much of this is threaded with stories of musicians and novelists. I think I had forgotten that Flaubert and Turgenev were friends and I remarked to myself "ah, that makes some sense, as I like them both." There was a place where he noted that Edith Wharton was friends with both William Dean Howells and Henry James. I do so like Wharton, but have read only one of the men - I must get to more of them.<br /><br />He has plenty of space in this to actually talk about death and dying, and doesn't just write about those who have gone before us. How is this for thought-provoking?<blockquote>Death and dying generate a whole questionnaire of such would-you-rathers. For a start, would you rather know you were dying, or not know? Would your rather watch, or not watch? ... Would you rather fear death or not fear it? That sounds an easy one. But how about this: what if you never gave death a thought, lived your life as if there were no tomorrow (there isn't by the way), took your pleasure, did your work, loved your family and then, as you were finally obliged to admit your own mortality, discovered that this new awareness of the full stop at the end of the sentence meant that the whole preceding story now made no sense at all? That if you'd fully realized to begin with that you were going to die, and what that meant, you would have lived according to quite different principles?</blockquote>Barnes is an atheist. The opening lines: "I don't believe in God, but I miss Him. That's what I say when the question is put." So, while he might not agree with Christianity's position on life after death, there is a lot of God in this also. I wasn't sure when I started writing this how I would rate it. In addition to being thought provoking, it was entertaining. I'm going to fill in all five stars because I think I will continue to think on bits of this for awhile.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3750832819015459539" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


