  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1876674385" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1876674385" />
    <a title="Girish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5924440-girish"><img alt="Girish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591866419p2/5924440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1876674385?book_show_action=true">Sep 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Girish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Girish" href="/user/show/5924440-girish">Girish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1876674385" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7451855933349571701"><i> &quot;What&apos;s all this about death, by the way?&quot; she continued. I explained that I didn&apos;t like the idea of it&quot; </i><br/><br/>I had put off this book simply because I feared it despite the authors helpful title. Books about death can have that effect on people. And yet, the book is more a medley of deaths, memory of deaths, process of dying, philosophy and faith. What makes it readable is Julian Barnes narrative.<br/><br/><i> &quot;A novelist is someone who remembers nothing yet records and manipulates different versions of what he </i></span>
  <span id="freeText7451855933349571701" style="display:none"><i> "What's all this about death, by the way?" she continued. I explained that I didn't like the idea of it" </i><br /><br />I had put off this book simply because I feared it despite the authors helpful title. Books about death can have that effect on people. And yet, the book is more a medley of deaths, memory of deaths, process of dying, philosophy and faith. What makes it readable is Julian Barnes narrative.<br /><br /><i> "A novelist is someone who remembers nothing yet records and manipulates different versions of what he doesn't remember" </i><br /><br />The essays aren't really coherent and he manages to squeeze in a bit of mystery from his own life in his own unique way. The multiple 'would-you-rather' scenarios really do get you confused and you end up becoming numb by the time he revisits the same 'event' with different lenses. The book also has some detailed bios/anecdotes from other authors and personalities who were part of Mr.Barnes research. Plus his favorite topic on memory and God! <br /><br />The parts where he ponders his own mortality, as a person and as an author are even funny. Specifically the part about his last reader - hilarious! See, we are talking of humour related to death and that is what the book can do to you. <br /><br />Is this a must read? No. Is this really good? No. And yet, should you ever bother to read this? Maybe when in the right frame of mind. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7451855933349571701" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

